         <h1>Hiroshi Teshigahara, 74, Avant-Garde Japanese Film Director </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Hiroshi Teshigahara , a celebrated Japanese filmmaker and grand master of the Sogetsu School for flower arrangement , died on Saturday at a hospital here . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 74 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was leukemia , his family said . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Teshigahara , who gained international acclaim for his avant-garde films and artwork , sent shock waves through the world of cinema in 1964 with the release of '' Suna no Onna '' ( '' Woman in the Dunes '' ) , a haunting , poetic and timeless metaphor made in Japan . <br><blue>5</blue>The film , written by Kobo Abe and based on a novel by him , won a special award at the Cannes International Film Festival and was nominated for an Academy Award for best director and best picture . <br><blue>6</blue>Noted for its technical brilliance , originality and power , the film featured a city-bred entomologist who is tricked into living with a widow whose shack rests at the bottom of a deep , inescapable sand pit , where he is forced to shovel sand endlessly . <br><blue>7</blue>The detainee finds entrapment and escape into his ultimate destiny . <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Teshigahara became interested in Surrealism and the avant-garde as an art student in the 1940 's . <br><blue>9</blue>In 1962 he made his first feature film , '' Otoshiana '' ( '' Pitfall '' ) , also written by Abe . <br><blue>10</blue>The director established his own production company and went on to make a series of films , often with Abe . <br><blue>11</blue>In addition to '' Woman in the Dunes , '' his films included '' Tanin no Kao '' ( '' The Face of Another '' ) in 1966 and '' Moetsukita Chizu '' ( '' The Ruined Map '' ) in 1968 . <br><blue>12</blue>In the late 1960 's Mr. Teshigahara was the toast of the international film community , appearing at festivals , collecting awards and promoting Japanese film . <br><blue>13</blue>After releasing '' Natsu no Heitai '' ( '' Summer Soldiers '' ) in 1972 , Mr. Teshigahara withdrew from feature filmmaking and turned his attention to ceramics and experimental cinema . <br><blue>14</blue>The director was the son of Sofu Teshigahara , the founder of the Sogetsu School of Ikebana , who was a leading figure in the movement that transformed traditional flower arrangement into a highly expressive art form . <br><blue>15</blue>In 1980 , after the death of his father and his sister , Mr. Teshigahara became the third head of the school , which reports 50,000 licensed followers and 450,000 students . <br><blue>16</blue>After a 17-year hiatus , Mr. Teshigahara returned to films in 1989 with '' Rikyu , '' about the subtle conflict between a petty warlord and a distinguished master of the ancient art of the tea ceremony . <br><blue>17</blue>It won the award for best artistic contribution at the Montreal World Film Festival . <br><blue>18</blue>His last film was '' Goh-hime '' ( '' Basara : The Princess Goh '' ) in 1992 . <br><blue>19</blue>He is survived by his wife , Toshiko Kobayashi , a former actress , and two daughters . <br><hr><br><blue>1(5)</blue>: <m_str>The director</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_11) 	<m_str>best director</m_str> (5_34) 	<m_str>The director</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_4) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>his films</m_str> (11_11) 	<m_str>his avant-garde films</m_str> (4_9) 	<br><blue>3(24)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (5_14) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_8) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (19_5) 	<m_str>Mr. Teshigahara</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_11) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_9) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_40) 	<m_str>Mr. Teshigahara</m_str> (15_14) 	<m_str>Abe</m_str> (9_22) 	<m_str>Mr. Teshigahara</m_str> (13_17) 	<m_str>1960 's Mr. Teshigahara</m_str> (12_4) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (13_25) 	<m_str>Mr. Teshigahara</m_str> (16_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_6) 	<m_str>The detainee</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str>his family</m_str> (3_6) 	<m_str>Kobo Abe</m_str> (5_6) 	<m_str>he</m_